<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-725-862  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 725 862.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 4 1989 v3 n36 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agencies forecast PC buys.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Page, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Microcomputer Survey Report issued by the General ServicesAdministration's (GSA) Information Resources Management Servicereflects the increase of microcomputer use by the federalgovernment.andP;  The report, released in 1987, showed a federalmicrocomputer inventory total of 490,361 at the end of fiscal 1987- 334,544 of which belonged to the Department of Defense (DOD).andO;Since then, many agencies have purchased large numbers ofmicrocomputers from GSA schedule contracts, although theacquisitions have not been reported to a central location.andP;  Mostagencies surveyed believe estimates of microcomputer use are low.andO;Three major DOD agencies expect to have at least 250,000 of themachines by the end of 1990.andP;  When this growth rate is projectedacross all federal agencies, the result is an estimated 1.5million microcomputers by the early 1990s.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Government Counselling Ltd. (reports).andO;Topic:     Government AgencyUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. General Services AdministrationMicrocomputersSurveyGrowth.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>